Lourenço implemented further government changes in October 2019, with Vera Esperanca dos Santos Daves appointed as Angola’s first female Minister of Finance on 8 October. Daves’ predecessor, Augusto Archer de Sousa Mangueira, was chosen as governor of Namibe province. On 21 January 2020, amid Angola’s ongoing economic crisis (see 
Economic Affairs
), da Costa was also replaced as Minister of the Economy and Planning by Sérgio de Sousa Mendes dos Santos. On the same day a new governor of Cunene province was named.

After the internal uprising in August 1998 against the regime of Laurent-Désiré Kabila in the DRC, the Angolan Government provided Kabila with military support. In October, as the conflict escalated in eastern DRC, Angola, in alliance with Namibia and Zimbabwe, pledged to continue supporting Kabila until the rebels were defeated. Following the assassination of Kabila in January 2001, the Angolan Government sent several thousand additional troops to the DRC. However, by the end of October 2002 Angola, Namibia and Zimbabwe had withdrawn all their troops. During 2008–09 the Angolan and Congolese authorities engaged in mutual expulsions of refugees from their respective territories. In 2009 an estimated 160,000 Congolese were expelled from Angola, while at least 30,000 Angolans were forcibly removed from the DRC. Although the two countries agreed in October 2009 to cease these activities, during 2010–18 Angola continued to expel large numbers of DRC nationals, many of whom were reportedly beaten, tortured or sexually assaulted. It was widely believed that the forced repatriations—which often affected illegal diamond miners from the DRC—reflected bilateral tensions over the control of natural resources along their disputed border. (The Angolan Government denied reports of the widespread mistreatment of DRC refugees, and claimed that the repatriations were in fact voluntary or that the DRC nationals were `irregular migrants’.) In August 2019, after many Congolese refugees had started to return to the DRC (see 
Refugees
), UNHCR signed a tripartite agreement with the Angolan and Congolese Governments concerning voluntary repatriation.

Meanwhile, recurrent Angolan incursions into the DRC (and Congo), ostensibly to monitor FLEC rebels, were also a source of discord. Amid the Congolese refugee crisis of 2017 (see 
Refugees
), in April the Angolan Government sent military reinforcements to its border with the DRC, with the stated aim of preventing armed Congolese militants from entering its territory.

In 2000 a French judicial inquiry was instigated into the alleged trafficking of arms to Angola by a French company, Brenco International, and a French businessman, Pierre Falcone. The company, along with a number of prominent French politicians, was alleged to have engaged in money laundering and the unauthorized sales of arms worth some US $600m. to the dos Santos Government in 1993–94. Falcone was placed under provisional detention in France in December 2000, but was released one year later. In April 2007 it was reported that 42 people, including Falcone and the Russian-Israeli businessman Arkadi Gaydamak (who was to be tried 
in absentia
), would face charges ranging from arms trafficking to tax evasion. Other notable defendants in the trial, which began in Paris in October 2008, were former French Minister of the Interior Charles Pasqua, and Jean-Christophe Mitterrand, son of former French President François Mitterrand. Of the 42 charged, none were Angolan nationals, although prosecutors claimed that many officials in that country, including dos Santos, had received tens of millions of dollars in illegal payments. In October 2009 Gaydamak and Falcone were each sentenced to six years’ imprisonment. Pasqua was jailed for three years (two suspended) and fined €100,000, while Jean-Christophe Mitterrand was given a two-year suspended sentence and fined €375,000. Following an appeal, in April 2011 a French court acquitted Pasqua and reduced the prison sentences imposed upon Falcone and Gaydamak to two-and-a-half years and three years, respectively.
